{"parse":{"title":"Cardiff Coloured Men's Christian Association","pageid":50180178,"revid":781487189,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Cardiff Coloured Men's Christian Association</b> was a Bible study and support organization started in 1902 in the port city of <a href=\"/wiki/Cardiff,_Wales\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cardiff, Wales\">Cardiff, Wales</a>, and mainly serving sailors from Africa, the Caribbean, the Indian subcontinent, North and South America.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Rev. John Hervey Boudier, a white clergyman and temperance advocate, started the Cardiff Coloured Men's Christian Association with weekly meetings in <a href=\"/wiki/St_Mary%27s_Church,_Cardiff\" title=\"St Mary&#39;s Church, Cardiff\">St. Mary's</a> vestry hall.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  Rev. Boudier soon founded dedicated quarters with a Coloured Men's Temperance Hotel in Cardiff, \"The Moon and Stars,\" in 1904,<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> and with an alcohol-free public house in <a href=\"/wiki/Tiger_Bay\" title=\"Tiger Bay\">Tiger Bay</a>, \"The Jolly Sailor,\" to serve the same visiting workers, who had few other options for respectable accommodation in the city.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>At its peak, the Association counted as many as 800 members.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> To raise funds for their activities, the Association held concerts and exhibitions, such as a stunt cyclist riding backwards to the Moon and Stars Hotel.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cardiff_Coloured_Men%27s_Christian_Association&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://hdl.handle.net/10107/4133684\">\"Notitle - Evening Express\"</a>. Walter Alfred Pearce. 1903-05-06<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-04-12</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Notitle+-+Evening+Express&amp;rft.pub=Walter+Alfred+Pearce&amp;rft.date=1903-05-06&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhdl.handle.net%2F10107%2F4133684&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACardiff+Coloured+Men%27s+Christian+Association\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=BoE4AQAAMAAJ&amp;lpg=PA280&amp;ots=MSt5hly9gj&amp;dq=Cardiff%20Coloured%20Men&#39;s%20Christian%20Association&amp;pg=PA280#v=onepage\">\"An 'All Black' Bible Class at Cardiff\"</a> <i>The Sketch</i> (D